metadata.name: GuilCity #143
metadata.description:
GuilCity is the beginning of an exciting journey bringing Guillaume Cornet‚Äôs densely-packed cities into the generative realm with the help of Matthew‚Äôs (@frostbitten‚Äôs) magic touch.

Matthew‚Äîwith his background in coding and animation‚Äîenables a new opportunity to experience these cities like never before. Numerous elements from vehicles to characters and even architecture have been given life. Interact with the city (computer mouse only): poke and peek around (even behind) in this active search & find journey! 

Each generative city fills the composition with the type of whimsical, expressive elements and characters you‚Äôve come to know Guil for. What kinds of wacky features have you discovered yet?

‚Äî

The tech behind this project utilizes the highly compressed WEBP image format in order to provide so many full-color options. This format is great, but unfortunately Safari on desktop/laptop must be upgraded to at least version 14 and macOS to at least version 11 Big Sur to use it.

The animation system for this project was created from scratch with additional help from the PIXI.js library for individual mesh animations.

‚Äî

To find out more about your GuilCity, copy your unique operation hash and place it at the end of the following url:
‚Ä¢ https://my.guil.city?fxhash=
(for example: https://my.guil.city?fxhash=ooezL8cffNJGSc4TfNQp3u3WnDpkg8J3zFRczLuumceoYU5QYPs)

‚Äî


The entire process has been a learning experience for both of us, adapting and exploring the many possibilities to interact with each others‚Äô skills and ideas.

We really enjoyed building this project together and are excited as we invite you to take a dive into your very own urban playground!

Merci √† tous! Cheers!
  - Guillaume Cornet, Matthew Seremet

metadata.name: Plottable Era: (I) Primitive #327
metadata.description:
'Plottable Era: (I) Primitive' is the first generator in the "Era" generators series, highlighting different periods and civilizations. This first series "Primitive" shows the beginning of mankind with people exploring the mountains and traveling on the sea during sunset.

The digital version simulates ink effects and adds a subtle animation over the water. Each outcome is also physically plottable with pens: A SVG file can be exported (right-click save) to plot the piece physically. The plots are designed to be executed in A4 format on either fountain pens (on white paper) or gel pens (Black / Blue).

Thanks to the utility token decoupling, you can get a physical version: the digital NFT is the recipe to a plottable art piece, owning it confers the right to plot or request a physical plot from @greweb (https://greweb.me/plots/nft). @greweb would use fountain pens but other plotting artists are free to achieve it with their own materials and ship to collectors ‚Äì as long as NFT is owned at request time.

More details and Source code: https://github.com/gre/gre/tree/master/doodles/plottable-era-primitive

@greweb ‚Äì 2022 ‚Äì tech: WebGL + Rust + WASM ‚Äì CC BY-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/

reserve is set to previous 2022 physical plot collectors.

metadata.name: ONE WORD (Ed.1) #100
metadata.description:
Inspired by the cut-up technique by William S. Burroughs, which was later used by David Bowie to create some of his song lyrics.

It generates a sequential list of a few hundred words that are placed at random locations on the canvas without overlapping.

Under the hood, a home-built spatial subdivision algorithm is used to look for empty spaces where the next random word might fit.

Originally, the plan was to publish this work with categorized words that somehow fit together into a theme, but after playing around with it, I found that this didn't match the original idea of the cut-up technique.
Also, it was very interesting to see completely arbitrary and unrelated words close together, forming incomplete fragments of a possible sentence. Just use your imagination!

The list of words was created while thinking about the current situation in the world and reading the news. Note, however, that it may happen that some words close to each other form a strange combination.

Press [S] to save in high resolution (long side = 4096 pixels).

Features:

Format - Portrait 40%, Landscape 40%, Square 20%
Canvas - Black 50%, White 50%
Background - Black 50%, White 50%
Post-Effects - None 33%, Light 33%, Strong 33%
Color Drop - Normal 50%, Inverse 50%

made with typescript and pixi.js


2022 // Karuma

metadata.name: Chaosplot #42
metadata.description:
Continued exploration of the algorithm from "Chaospill" with a symmetric two tone style that is plotter friendly. The result can be rotated to whatever orientation works best for your display purposes. The code is presented unminified with comments and will be open sourced soon.

Live Mode Controls

Click to regenerate with a different starting seed.
1 - Save a SVG, the result is sized for 11"x17" prints with each color on a separate layer
2 - Save a PNG of the output
3 - Switch paper size to 8.5"x11" letter or A1 for different size plots
4 - Toggle HD mode which increases resolution and disables noise for printing
